snippet.textDisplay:
Hi everyone, hope you're well! Wanted to share something quickly please... I've just finished a workout DVD which I've not done in months. Regular YWA has not only built a surprising amount of strength & stamina while said DVD gathered dust but even better, Adriene's supportive words rang clear in my mind throughout, 'soften the skin of the face; focus on the breath; lift the corners of the mouth.... just a little; how you move is important; what signals are you sending if you jerk yourself around'.
It was immensely encouraging & humbling to notice simultaneously the mental & physical benefits of just a few months of practicing YWA & how these things are manifesting off the mat.
Have a great practice everyone! 💖 #holdinghandssavasana

snippet.textDisplay:
Thank you, thank you so much Adriene for your light and love. MARY OLIVER is one of my dearest poets and guides.
With deep gratitude from Comox, Vancouver Island, BC, Canada


"Every day,
I see or hear
something
that more or less

kills me
with delight,
that leaves me
like a needle


in the haystack
of light.
It is what I was born for--
to look, to listen,


to lose myself
inside this soft world--
to instruct myself
over and over


in joy,
and acclamation.
Nor am I talking
about the exceptional,


the fearful, the dreadful,
the very extravagant--
but of the ordinary,
the common, the very drab


the daily presentations.
Oh, good scholar,
I say to myself,
how can you help


but grow wise
with such teachings
as these--
the untrimmable light


of the world,
the ocean's shine,
the prayers that are made
out of grass?


Mary Oliver"

snippet.textDisplay: Day 4 is done and my head cold is clearing up! I really loved today's practice. I started yoga about 3 years ago with a trauma-sensitive class specific to survivors of sexual assault. I was very uncomfortable at first, but the class was so compassionate and kind (the teacher reminds me of you, Adriene!) that I stuck through the discomfort. I remember the first pose I really, really connected with was Warrior 2. It was the first time I felt powerful and safe in my body. Can't wait for day 5!

I was very uncomfortable at first, but the class was so compassionate and kind (the teacher reminds me of you, Adriene!) that I stuck through the discomfort. I remember the first pose I really, really connected with was Warrior 2. It was the first time I felt powerful and safe in my body. Can't wait for day 5!

snippet.textDisplay: Today I feel much more awake moving into Day 4. One known tenet, that I had not necessarily forgotten, but has definitely been dormant within myself for much too long, was love. Instead, despite many achievements in the past several years, I consistently began to loathe aspects of myself. Like how long it would take to get things done, how forgetful I was getting, how much of my time was being used up. It was a slow process that took me out of myself, and then I would look in the mirror and be shocked at what I saw. Yesterday I awakened and remembered that loathing activates sickness and pain, whereas actively loving brings healing and well- being. So that is how I entered today’s practice! From the first focused breath I activated the energy slowly and lovingly to each joint and muscle! The pace was precisely what I needed and the instruction was wonderful! My mind still likes to think that I can do, what I could do, just four years ago when I was very fit! Remembering and practicing the beginning forms is what will strengthen me and build the flexibility I need. That is what will actively get me to where I want to be. Just yesterday I would have loathed not being able to keep up in high lunge. But today, staying in low lunge, I lovingly focused on breath and form to activate a positive flow of energy within myself and healing. Thank you Adriene!

snippet.textDisplay: Something curious happened in the last standing pose.   Normally I'm very conscious of my breath when breathing deeply.  My mind says "breath in, breath out, breath in, breath out."  But when I arrived at the last standing pose, I noticed my body was breathing beautifully, deeply, and richly all on its own.  My mind was just observing, not directing.  It was such a magical moment as though my body was waking up after a long slumber.  Thank you.

snippet.textDisplay: Day 4 done. I have to say how amazing it is to have such a high quality and well considered yoga programme for absolutely free!! Normally something like this would cost tens if not hundreds of dollars! It's one thing to do a random yoga practice now and then, but it's a different experience to commit to daily practice and to follow a structured programme. I actually feel improvements already, much more than last year when I was just doing random daily workouts with no structure and not much thought either. Thank you Adriene for your amazing work and sharing it with us.

snippet.textDisplay: When I saw 'Activate' there was a part of me thinking, this is a core yoga practice, but I loved that it embrace activating all part of the body, mind and breath. I have a hamstring injury, which is on the road to healing and so the forward folds aren't as easy as before, but I am getting there and being mindful of how I go into the pose. I was surprised that the knee of the floor lunge was ok on the hamstring injured leg. I think that this 30-day yoga journey will go a long way to helping with the healing process. Namaste xo

snippet.textDisplay:
The feeling and image of energy traveling up the front of my body and down the back and around again is going to stay with me. It's a powerful, and, yes, activating, feeling to be the center of that flowing energy. Thank you for that and all of it.

During the last mountain pose, I heard in my head Dorothy from the Wizard of Oz saying, "There's no place like home." Then I realized how appropriate for this 30 day Home practice that my husband, daughter and I began the new year by starting to watch Wizard of Oz 19 1/2 minutes before midnight so that when Dorothy opens to the door to her house that has just landed in Oz and the film transitions from black and white to color would happen just as the new year/new decade began. It felt like a good way to symbolize the optimism I want to embrace about this new year. I didn't think about it at the time that the message of the film is that what you're searching for was right in front of you all the time. A very yoga, very Yoga with Adriene, kind of message. So, thank you for another wonderful day of yoga, Adriene and everyone else sharing the journey.

Sending much love to you and Benji :)

snippet.textDisplay: My exercise induced asthma really started getting the best of me during the taller warrior poses. Instead of gritting through and probably starting an asthma attack, I released, sat on the mat, and put my health first and directed my energy to connect with my breath. I always feel silly to not push through something, but this time I let my pride go and listened to my body. Thank you Adrienne for validating that sometimes all you can do is breathe. ❤ learning to forgive myself for my short comings, and to stop the constant push for excellence is an obstacle I didn't know I would face in the first hour of my day. Thank you for your warm heart and validating that it's ok to listen and just breathe ❤
